How many seats in the Legislative Yuan will the Kuomintang party win in the next Taiwan parliamentary elections? Hattip to @V-Y- and @sebawi for thier insights which reduced my enthusism for KMT seats.

- The DPP now holds 68 out of 113 seats, while the KMT has 35 seats. - Opposition party likely to' grow because of disaffection-ed ruling party voters) - Undecided voters - presumably inclined to KMT - may be lured to 3rd Parties

Looking at the news, it seems less and less plausible that the KMT will gain more than 42 seats, while it seems more and more plausible that they may repeat their devastating result from the last election. However, a lot depends on the undecided voters that are mostly regarded as KMT-friendly but have not decided upon their choice [1]. PFP may step in the breach.

How many seats in the Legislative Yuan will the Kuomintang party win in the next Taiwan parliamentary elections? Hattip to @cafebedouin for cogent analysis and to @sebawi for an execellent overview. More parties = fewer seats.

In contrast to the presidential race, the results of the parliamentary elections are affected by a number of additional factors. In the legislative election, there are other considerations at work than in the presidential election [4]. Latest developments and information require me to adjust the foreast: first, there are the latest - and final - polls [1], second, the support of PFP candidates by Foxconn founder Terry Gou [2], third, the relevance of the party lists in this election [3] and, fourth, the large margin of undecided voters [7].

More parties, fewer undecided. Most likely result is election will push % into the low 30s, which will edge up the number of seats a bit higher than last round. But, they probably need to get +35% to get more than 42, which seems pretty unlikely.
Initial prediction.

They are currently polling at ~ 24 to 33% (depending on the poll), which translates to about 27 to 37 seats (if popular vote were to equal number of seats, which is NEVER the case...). My first guess is based on simple / simplistic / simpleton's logic from those polls, and nothing else.

Though Taiwan actually has a mixed system of first-past-the-post presidential and district candidate elections and proportional representation (PR) party votes, I will just assume for simplicity's sake that opinion polling on the legislative election roughly reflects what the outcome will be.
*changed probabilities from 49% to 47% (>36) and from 47% to 49% (36<x<42)

Taking into consideration that the results of the last election (DPP: 68 seats; KMT: 35 seats) were largely influenced by extraordinary factors (Sunflower Movement, Swap of KMT Candidate), it is not heretic to assume that they are able to gain more seats in the 2020 polls. Analysis of current predictions and election system
Considering past election results and recent Kuomingtanfg's campaign, it seems that they won't be able to exceed the last election results, i.e., 35 seats.

The increasingly polarized politics of the region will foment more anti-Communist sentiment especially in a state such as Taiwan, but much depends on Chinese actions in Hong Kong between now and the year's end.

With the situation in Hong Kong persisting, Taiwanese voters will, either consciously or unconsciously, feel an urge to express their anti-Communism. In the last few elections, the party has lost seats and this trend is due to change so the party will build upon 35 seats.
